name: Trello Development
desc:
Trello board used by the Trello team to track work on Trello. How meta!

The development of the Trello API is being tracked at https://trello.com/api

The development of Trello Mobile applications is being tracked at https://trello.com/mobile

cards.desc:
The Trello team actively participates on this board, and uses it to communicate with the outside world about its development priorities.

#Organization

##Ideas
Check out the Ideas list here first. If you like a feature, add your vote. See [Submitting feature requests for Trello](http://help.trello.com/customer/portal/articles/990807-submitting-feature-requests-for-trello) for info on how to submit a new request.

## Known Issues
These are things, usually bugs, that we know about, but haven't had time to move into the schedule. In essence, they're pecadillos we're asking our users to live with.

##Next Up
 "Announcing your plans is a good way to hear God laugh." - Al Swearengen.

##In Progress
There's probably a person thinking about this right now.

##Testing
Measure twice. Cut once.

##Live
We keep several **Live** lists so you can see things that went out a while back.

#Responsiveness

We understand coming to rely on a tool, and how quickly elation can turn to frustration when you brush against the same sharp edge a dozen times a day.

The entire team is actively using this board, but the leftmost columns will see much less frequent updates than the others.

Thanks for bearing with us and thanks for your continued feedback and support. 

#Feedback

[Trello Help](https://trello.com/help) will always contain the best way to get in touch with us.

If you have something nice to say, say it on Twitter or Facebook to spread the goodness of Trello. If you have something grumpy to say, we're not saying you shouldn't do it on social networks. (We can take it.) But maybe give us a shout at support@trello.com before you really trash us. :)

#Mobile
... is a whole other kettle of fish. Please see https://trello.com/ios and https://trello.com/android

#Comments? Ideas?
Please see https://trello.com/help for how to give feedback. Please don't comment on this card. We'd like to keep it clean for new users.
cards.name: What can you expect from this board?

cards.desc:
#Summary

This card represents a range of requests, mostly having to do with keeping track of the amount of time a user spends on the task represented by a given card or checklist item, and making that information useful to the user or their organization.

**Note:** There is a 3rd party app that does burndown charts: https://trello.com/c/d7I1huVB 

**Harvest Chrome Extension:** The fine folks at Harvest have built a Chrome Extension that let's you track your time in Harvest directly from your Trello boards. http://www.getharvest.com/trello

**BoardTrail:** Track the time that your cards are in the 'Doing' list of your board. https://boardtrail.com

**Paydirt:** Time tracking that integrates with multiple webapps via a browser extension, including Trello: https://paydirtapp.com/time-tracking-in-trello


#Key Points

Here's a summary of the discussion so far:

 - Integrating with Harvest or LiquidPlanner would be nice
 - Estimated vs. Actual Hours would be helpful
 - Reporting and analytics would be helpful
 - Pomodoro has been mentioned a few times, but it's not clear that it doesn't need its own card
 - Time tracking as a core feature of Trello would complicate the product

#Outlook
User feedback has been consistent with our feeling that this is better implemented as a plug-in, rather than as a core Trello feature. We'll definitely revisit this when the plug-in architecture is in progress.

----------

cards.desc:
#Summary
This functionality would help people find cards and understand the contents of long lists by allowing them to sort the cards in a list.

#Difficulties
Card order within a list is meaningful. When you change the order of cards in a list, it means something and is reported in a notification. This presents special challenges for the design of any sorting functionality we might consider.

When you sort, who sees it? You or everyone? Is it reported to everyone? What if you inadvertently sort and destroy a list order that was meaningful? Do we need to offer recovery/undo options?

If sorting is just for finding cards, do we offer the ability to sort only for your current view of the interface? How do we reflect that to you so that you don't think you've re-sorted for everyone? What happens if someone changes the order of a list while you have it sorted?

We would need to support sorting temporarily, for viewing, in which case you wouldn't be able to reorder the cards, and everyone else would see the current order, and "solidifying" that sort, which would be reported ("Rich Armstrong reordered the Ideas list by Votes.")

There's clear value in being able to find things in lists, but sorting can be really problematic.

#Key Points

- Due dates seem to get a disproportionate amount of attention for this request, which may mean that just a better way to visualize what's due would suffice here


#Outlook
For the foreseeable future, we're likely to focus on improving filtering before tackling any sorting.

If we get more clarity from our users as to what they'd find intuitive, it'd definitely help.


----------

cards.desc:
#Summary
Data export is available for each board and card under the **Share, Print, and Export** link on every board and card. This export is suitable for backups and for technical usages, but not very useful for non-technical users.

You can also just **.json** to a card url, or /board.json to the end of a board URL. This will download a .json text file directly to your computer.

You have to be logged in to download a backup of a board that can't be seen publicly.

#Key Points
Here's a summary of the discussion so far:

 - CSV export would be welcome 
 - This is key for making reports
 - Importing of cards is not part of the scope of this feature
 
#Outlook
We'd like to solve this problem for people, but need much more feedback about what would be useful.

#Alternate Solutions:

 - [TrelloExport Extension](https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/trelloexport/nhdelomnagopgaealggpgojkhcafhnin?hl=en) for Google Chrome - [source code](https://github.com/llad/trelloExport). Thanks @markwoodall!

cards.desc:
This is a general card for the idea that a card's life can happen in multiple boards, rather than having a single card that moves from list to list, and sometimes board to board.

There's definite value in this, but the amount of interface complexity it adds could be quite high if not designed correctly. It might be better to have "joined" cards, where someone who can see both boards would be able to see sibling cards. 

If you're a designer and you have ideas about how this could best be implemented, please don't be shy. Send us a mockup at feature-ideas@trello.com.

Some valuable feedback we've gotten:

 > This would be tricky to implement in a fashion that makes sense to most users from a privacy standpoint. If a card lives on both a public and private boards, the private board will have to have a notice and icon that clearly shows all underlying information is publicly viewable -- **Lorin Halpert**
cards.name: Cards live on multiple boards

cards.desc:
#Summary
The ability to change the background color/texture/picture of a board or list.

> Per-board backgrounds would make it harder to accidentally
> be on the wrong board, and quicker for our brains to 
> associate the board we're looking at when restoring the 
> window." -- Andy M.

> If we have a couple of "to-do" lists and a couple of "done"
> lists, it would be nice to be able to change the background
> color of the to-do lists so they stand out a bit more." -- Ryan L.

#Key Points
- The Stylebot Chrome extension is a possible workaround for technical folks
- "This would be great because I tend to set up two distinct kinds of lists and would love an easy way to visually differentiate between them."
- There's a few folks who want to be able to change a card's background color. That might be a separate feature.
- Some folks want this as a way to align Trello's look more closely with their organization
- Many boards have one or more lists that serve a different purpose (e.g., shopping list, or the Trello Dev Board's Ideas list itself). It'd be great to have these be visually distinct

#Outlook
